            deepDive: "The Four Major Classes of Phylum Arthropoda and their exact distinguishing traits: 1. Class Insecta (Insects - housefly, mosquito, butterfly, bee, cockroach, grasshopper, termite, mantis): Body divided strictly into 3 segments (Head, Thorax, Abdomen), exactly 3 pairs of jointed legs (6 legs) attached to the thorax, usually 1 or 2 pairs of wings on the thorax (except wingless fleas/lice), 1 pair of antennae (feelers), compound eyes (plus simple ocelli), and breathe through spiracles and branching tracheal tubes along the abdomen/thorax. 2. Class Arachnida (Arachnids - spiders, scorpions, ticks, mites): Body divided strictly into 2 segments (fused Cephalothorax and Abdomen), exactly 4 pairs of jointed legs (8 legs), NO wings, NO antennae (feelers), possess chelicerae/pedipalps and poison fangs/stingers. 3. Class Crustacea (Crustaceans - crabs, lobsters, crayfish, woodlice, water fleas/Daphnia): Mostly aquatic (breathing with gills), body divided into 2 segments (cephalothorax protected by hard carapace and abdomen), between 5 to 10 pairs of jointed legs (including front pincers/claws), and 2 pairs of antennae. 4. Class Myriapoda (Chilopoda & Diplopoda - many-legged segment animals): Centipedes (Class Chilopoda - flattened ribbon body, exactly 1 pair of legs per segment, fast carnivorous hunters equipped with poison claws under the head) vs Millipedes (Class Diplopoda - cylindrical rounded body, exactly 2 pairs of legs per segment, slow herbivorous/detritivore recyclers that coil up tightly when touched and secrete offensive defensive fluids).",
