            deepDive: "Three Modes of Heat Transfer: 1. Conduction (occurs strictly inside solids, especially metals like copper, iron, and aluminum where heat energy is passed from hot vibrating particle to neighboring particle without the atoms changing their physical positions. Good conductors allow fast heat flow e.g. metal saucepans and frying pans; Insulators / Poor conductors block heat flow e.g. wooden spoon handles, plastic kettle grips, dry cotton cloth, air, and asbestos), 2. Convection (occurs inside fluids: liquids and gases. When water at the bottom of a kettle is heated by a stove, it expands, becomes less dense/lighter, and rises upward to the top, while cold, denser water at the top sinks down to take its place, creating a continuous circulatory loop called a Convection Current. Convection explains how rooms are ventilated via high ventilators, how water boils, and how Land and Sea breezes occur along Lake Victoria), and 3. Radiation (the transfer of heat energy across empty space or transparent air in the form of electromagnetic infrared rays without requiring any material particles at all. Radiation explains how solar heat reaches Earth from the Sun across 150 million kilometers of vacuum space, or how your hands feel warm instantly when held sideways near a burning campfire without touching the flames).",
