            options: [
              { id: "a", text: "Communicable diseases (such as Malaria, Cholera, Tuberculosis, Measles, Influenza, Ringworm, and HIV/AIDS) are caused by pathogenic biological germs (Bacteria, Viruses, Protozoa, and Fungi) and can spread directly or indirectly from an infected person (or vector) to a healthy person; whereas Non-Communicable diseases (such as Nutritional Anemia, Kwashiorkor, Rickets, Scurvy, Asthma, Hypertension, Diabetes, and Cancer) are NOT caused by germs and CANNOT spread from one person to another (caused instead by dietary deficiencies, genetics, lifestyle, or organ wear and tear)", correct: true },
              { id: "b", text: "Communicable diseases only affect cattle, while non-communicable only affect plants", correct: false },
              { id: "c", text: "Communicable diseases are cured by drinking milk, while non-communicable require surgery", correct: false },
              { id: "d", text: "Both categories mean exact common headaches caused by cold wind", correct: false },
            ],
            explanation: "Understanding disease classification allows correct prevention: you immunize and isolate against communicable diseases (measles/polio), but you fix diet and lifestyle (eating balanced diets and exercising) against non-communicable diseases (diabetes/hypertension/rickets).",
            deepDive: "Four Modes of Spread of Communicable Diseases: 1. Airborne / Droplet Infection (spread when an infected person coughs, sneezes, spits, or talks inside crowded unventilated rooms, releasing microscopic moisture droplets containing germs that healthy people inhale e.g. Tuberculosis TB, Pneumonia, Influenza, Measles, Whooping Cough, Diphtheria, Chickenpox, and COVID-19; prevented by good ventilation, covering mouth when coughing, and childhood vaccination), 2. Waterborne / Foodborne Fecal-Oral Spread (spread when people drink unboiled water or eat food contaminated by human feces containing germs, often carried by mechanical vector houseflies e.g. Cholera, Typhoid fever, Dysentery, Polio, Hepatitis A, and Roundworms; prevented by boiling drinking water, proper latrine use, handwashing with soap, and VIP latrines), 3. Vector-Borne Spread (spread by blood-sucking or mechanical insect/snail vectors e.g. Malaria via female Anopheles mosquito, Sleeping Sickness via Tsetse fly, Bilharzia via freshwater snails, Plague via rat fleas, and East Coast Fever via brown ear ticks; prevented by sleeping under ITNs, draining stagnant pools, and acaricide dipping), and 4. Direct Contact & Blood/Sexual Spread (spread by direct touching of infected skin or exchange of infected body fluids e.g. Ringworm, Scabies, Leprosy, Ebola, and Red Eye/Conjunctivitis via contact; and HIV/AIDS, Syphilis, and Gonorrhea via unprotected sexual contact, sharing unsterilized needles/razor blades, or mother-to-child; prevented by personal hygiene, not sharing towels/blades, and strict abstinence).",
